  {
    "user": "UCUSW7WVD",
    "type": "message",
    "ts": "1742841274.530649",
    "client_msg_id": "31ff2660-d9be-441f-8f3c-404883e85134",
    "text": "<@UL2SJ88Q3> Yes, and I used to do this as well for a long time. If you have n bugs to avoid in a system (Christopher Alexander calls them misfits) but your design process can only handle n-2, ping-ponging can result, often over a time of months as a bug gets reported in production, gets fixed, the other bug gets created, gets reported in production..\n\nA lot of the value of tests for me is shortcutting this sort of ping-ponging between bugs. But if you tell AI to write the tests, and give AI _carte blanche_ to modify tests at any time.. :man-shrugging::skin-tone-4:",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1742830403.707769",
    "parent_user_id": "UC2A2ARPT",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "ets4z",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "user",
                "user_id": "UL2SJ88Q3"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " Yes, and I used to do this as well for a long time. If you have n bugs to avoid in a system (Christopher Alexander calls them misfits) but your design process can only handle n-2, ping-ponging can result, often over a time of months as a bug gets reported in production, gets fixed, the other bug gets created, gets reported in production..\n\nA lot of the value of tests for me is shortcutting this sort of ping-ponging between bugs. But if you tell AI to write the tests, and give AI "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "carte blanche",
                "style": {
                  "italic": true
                }
              },
              {
